<link href="adcp.css" rel="stylesheet"><entry><xh5>break the wind • break wind</xh5><p> <i>break the wind—</i>said of a line of trees, fence, etc. which gives protection against the wind: The dunes <u>break the wind</u> on the beach and provide a beautiful background.</p><p> <i>break wind</i>—(euph., also: pass wind) expel intestinal gas from the anus: I’ll kill the first son of a bitch who even <u>breaks wind</u>.</p><p> <div class="note">Note</div> Neither expression correlates in meaning with the compound <b>broken-winded</b>—(also: wind-broken) used of a horse that has impaired breathing: The train was heavy, and where there was any incline the two engines grunted like <u>brokenwinded</u> horses.</p> </entry>
